ut the three most likely plans.\n\nHowever, no decision will be made at next week\'s meeting.','Butler Board Sets Timeline For Consolidation Decision','','publish','closed','open','','butler-board-sets-timeline-for-consolidation-decision','','','2014-12-09 22:52:56','2014-12-09 22:52:56','',184,'http://militiatoday.com/topic/butler-board-sets-timeline-for-consolidation-decision/',0,'topic','',0),(193,1,'2014-12-09 22:55:24','2014-12-09 22:55:24','<a href=\"http://www.ask4direct.com/images/info/956313.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://www.ask4direct.com/images/info/956313.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"153\" height=\"180\" /></a>The BC3 Education Foundation has teamed up with C.W. Howard Insurance to establish a new scholarship.\n\nThe C.W. Howard Insurance Family Scholarship will be awarded for the first time during the 2015-2016 school year to a 2015 graduate of the Cardinal Wuerl North Catholic High School who is attending Butler County Community College. The monetary amount was not specified.\n\nThe scholarship is meant to inspire a new generation of community leaders in Butler County.\n\nFor more information about the Butler County Community College Scholarship Program, visit www.bc3.edu.','BC3 Announces New Scholarship','','publish','closed','open','','bc3-announces-new-scholarship','','','2014-12-09 22:56:37','2014-12-09 22:56:37','',184,'http://militiatoday.com/topic/bc3-announces-new-scholarship/',0,'topic','',0),(195,1,'2014-12-09 22:59:25','2014-12-09 22:59:25','<img id=\"__wp-temp-img-id\" src=\"http://www.ask4direct.com/images/info/956482.jpg\" alt=\"Butler County, Pennsylvania\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" />\n\nA problem in the construction of the roof on the new downtown Butler County office building could cost as much as $50,000.\n\nThe Butler County commissioners discussed the error during Monday\'s agenda-setting meeting.\n\nOfficials say a \'discrepancy in the drawings\' led to the roof being installed without a slope to drain rainwater. The problem is being corrected by installing insulation.\n\nBoard chairman Bill McCarrier said he is concerned with the problem but noted the $11 million project is still coming in under budget because of some changes to the scope of work.\n\nThe building will sit on South Washington Street next to the Butler County Government Center and house county human services.','Roof Error Could Cost County $50,000','','publish','closed','open','','roof-error-could-cost-county-50000','','','2014-12-09 23:17:19','2014-12-09 23:17:19','',184,'http://militiatoday.com/topic/roof-error-could-cost-county-50000/',0,'topic','',0),(202,1,'2014-12-09 23:36:20','2014-12-09 23:36:20','Chester Suski\'s friends and family knew he was a strong believer in the merits of hard work. “He worked until he was 90,” said his son, James Suski of Murrysville. Chester John “C.J.” Suski of Jefferson Hills, formerly of Whitehall, died of congestive heart failure in Jefferson Hospital on Saturday, Dec. 6, 2014. He was 91.\r\n\r\nA World War II veteran, Mr. Suski was the longtime owner of W.S. Radcliffe Co. in Wilkinsburg, which sells automotive paints, mostly to body shops and car dealers. “He enjoyed the camaraderie between the people. He enjoyed people,” his son said. Mr. Suski grew up in Lawrenceville, the son of Michael and Marianna Suski. A 1941 Schenley High School graduate, he enlisted in the Army at the start of World War II and served with the 7th Armored Division of Gen. George S. Patton\'s Third Army, his family said. He remained in the military until the end of the war in 1945.\r\n\r\nIn 1947, Mr. Suski married Josephine Pavlik, with whom he had four sons. In his spare time, Mr. Suski enjoyed fishing, gardening and playing cards with friends. In addition to his sons James and Kenneth, Mr. Suski is survived by sons Bob Suski of Brentwood and Dr. David Suski of Hampton; nine grandchildren; and six great-grandchildren. He was preceded in death by his wife of 61 years, Josephine Suski, and his siblings, Cecelia Zaleski, James Suski, Bernadine Mindzekiwiec, Irene Sonick and Sally Oldynski.\r\n\r\nFamily and friends will be received from 2 to 4 and 7 to 9 p.m. Tuesday in Jefferson Memorial Funeral Home Inc., 301 Curry Hollow Road, Pleasant Hills. A Mass of Christian Burial will be celebrated at 10 a.m. Wednesday in St. Gabriel of the Sorrowful Virgin. Entombment will follow in Jefferson Memorial Park.\r\n','Chester John Suski','','publish','open','closed','','chester-john-suski','','','2015-02-18 10:24:06','2015-02-18 10:24:06','',0,'http://militiatoday.com/?post_type=bepro_listings&#038;p=202',0,'bepro_listings','',0),(203,1,'2014-12-09 23:39:23','2014-12-09 23:39:23','[caption id=\"attachment_206\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"217\"]<a href=\"http://militiatoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/sdfghsdfg.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-206\" src=\"http://militiatoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/sdfghsdfg-217x300.jpg\" alt=\"Carl E. Janusek\" width=\"217\" height=\"300\" /></a> Carl E. Janusek[/caption]\r\n\r\nIf they hailed from Western Pennsylvania or recorded an album in Pittsburgh from the 1940s through the \'60s, it is likely “Mon Valley Musicologist” Carl Janusek knew as much about the artists as anyone. “If anybody needed to know any information on any Pittsburgh artist, group or song, he was the man to go to,” said Fred Bohn, owner of Attic Records in Millvale. “He\'d been researching them since being a kid. The passion for the music was deep.”\r\n\r\nCarl E. Janusek of Duquesne died Friday, Dec. 5, 2014, in UPMC Shadyside. He was 71. He was a son of the late Edward D. and Mary Kanyak Janusek. He joined the Army during the Vietnam War era and later worked for more than 40 years as a meat inspector for the Department of Agriculture. He retired in 2008. Mr. Janusek loved music, said Eileen Stefl of Greensburg, his girlfriend of 15 years.\r\n\r\nFriends will be received from 4 to 8 p.m. Monday in Maloy-Schleifer Funeral Home, 915 Kennedy Ave., Duquesne. A blessing service will be held in the funeral home at 1:30 p.m. Tuesday, followed by a Mass of Christian Burial at 2 p.m. in St. Joseph Catholic Church, 817 W. Grant Ave., Duquesne. Burial with military honors will be in St. Joseph Cemetery in West Mifflin.','Carl E. Janusek','','publish','open','closed','','carl-e-janusek','','','2015-02-18 10:29:24','2015-02-18 10:29:24','',0,'http://militiatoday.com/?post_type=bepro_listings&#038;p=203',0,'bepro_listings','',0),(204,1,'2014-12-09 23:35:38','2014-12-09 23:35:38','Chester John Suski','Chester John Suski','Chester John Suski','inherit','open','open','','dt-common-streams-streamserver-cls','','','2014-12-09 23:35:56','2014-12-09 23:35:56','',202,'http://militiatoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/dt.common.streams.StreamServer.cls_.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(206,1,'2014-12-09 23:37:59','2014-12-09 23:37:59','Carl E. Janusek','Carl E. Janusek','Carl E. Janusek','inherit','open','open','','sdfghsdfg','','','2014-12-09 23:38:14','2014-12-09 23:38:14','',203,'http://militiatoday.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/sdfghsdfg.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(209,1,'2014-12-09 23:59:31','2014-12-09 23:59:31','[create_listing_form registration=1]','Submit a Listing','','publish','closed','closed','','submit-a-listing','','','2014-12-10 13:47:46','2014-12-10 13:47:46','',0,'http://militiatoday.com/?page_id=209',0,'page','',0),(211,1,'2014-12-10 00:00:28','2014-12-10 00:00:28','[display_listings l_type=19]\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Click to submit\" href=\"http://militiatoday.com/submit-a-listing/\" target=\"_blank\">Click to submit</a> your Obituary.','Obituaries','','publish','open','open','','obits','','','2015-02-18 10:18:21','2015-02-18 10:18:21','',0,'http://militiatoday.com/?page_id=211',0,'page','',0),(219,1,'2014-12-10 01:31:44','2014-12-10 01:31:44','Pennsylvania News','Pennsylvania News','','publish','closed','open','','pennsylvania-news','','','2014-12-10 01:31:44','2014-12-10 01:31:44','',115,'http://militiatoday.com/?post_type=forum&#038;p=219',0,'forum','',0),(222,1,'2014-12-10 08:33:32','2014-12-10 08:33:32','Militia News brought to you by Militia Today','Militia News','','publish','open','open','','militia-news','','','2014-12-10 08:33:32','2014-12-10 08:33:32','',0,'http://militiatoday.com/?page_id=222',0,'page','',0),(228,1,'2014-12-10 08:58:03','2014-12-10 08:58:03','<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://iamtheteaparty.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/colonial-militia.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"380\" height=\"260\" />BOSTON, Mass. — National guard units seeking to confiscate a cache of recently banned assault weapons were ambushed on April 19th by elements of a para-military extremist faction. Military and law enforcement sources estimate that 72 were killed and more than 200 injured before government forces were compelled to withdraw.\r\n\r\nSpeaking after the clash, Massachusetts Governor Thomas Gage declared that the extremist faction, which was made up of local citizens, has links to the radical right-wing tax protest movement. Gage blamed the extremists for recent incidents of vandalism directed against internal revenue offices. The governor, who described the group\'s organizers as \"criminals,\" issued an executive order authorizing the summary arrest of any individual who has interfered with the government\'s efforts to secure law and order. The military raid on the extremist arsenal followed wide-spread refusal by the local citizenry to turn over recently outlawed assault weapons.\r\n\r\nGage issued a ban on military-style assault weapons and ammunition earlier in the week. This decision followed a meeting in early this month between government and military leaders at which the governor authorized the forcible confiscation of illegal arms.\r\n\r\nOne government official, speaking on condition of anonymity, pointed out that \"none of these people would have been killed had the extremists obeyed the law and turned over their weapons voluntarily.\" Government troops initially succeeded in confiscating a large supply of outlawed weapons and ammunition. However, troops attempting to seize arms and ammunition in Lexington met with resistance from heavily-armed extremists who had been tipped off regarding the government\'s plans. During a tense standoff in Lexington \'s town park, National Guard Colonel Francis Smith, commander of the government operation, ordered the armed group to surrender and return to their homes. The impasse was broken by a single shot, which was reportedly fired by one of the right-wing extremists. Eight civilians were killed in the ensuing exchange.\r\n\r\nIronically, the local citizenry blamed government forces rather than the extremists for the civilian deaths. Before order could be restored, armed citizens from surrounding areas had descended upon the guard units. Colonel Smith, finding his forces overmatched by the armed mob, ordered a retreat.\r\n\r\nGovernor Gage has called upon citizens to support the state/national joint task force in its effort to restore law and order. The governor also demanded the surrender of those responsible for planning and leading the attack against the government troops. Samuel Adams, Paul Revere, and John Hancock, who have been identified as \"ringleaders\" of the extremist faction, remain at large.\r\n\r\nAnd this, people, is how the American Revolution began.\r\n\r\nApril 20, 1775','Seventy-two killed resisting gun confiscation in Boston','','publish','open','open','','seventy-two-killed-resisting-gun-confiscation-in-boston','','','2014-12-10 09:31:35','2014-12-10 09:31:35','',0,'http://militiatoday.com/?p=228',0,'post','',0),(231,1,'2014-12-10 09:47:58','2014-12-10 09:47:58',' ','','militia-news','publish','open','open','','231','','','2015-02-06 08:58:15','2015-02-06 08:58:15','',0,'http://militiatoday.com/?p=231',3,'nav_menu_item','',0),(232,1,'2014-12-10 09:47:35','2014-12-10 09:47:35','<div class=\"entry-content clearfix\">\r\n\r\n<strong>UNDER CONSTRUCTIO